image.altText: Sam Kerr pumps her right fist as she looks to the crowd after the Matildas defeated France.

items.synopsis: In the wake of the Matildas' pulsating quarterfinal win over France, captain Sam Kerr is adamant her side is not done yet as they look ahead to a blockbuster clash with England.

title.children: 'That's what we're here for': Kerr confident Matildas can keep World Cup dream rolling

image.altText: MatildasvFrance (3)

items.synopsis: The Matildas find yet another cult hero, a star mourns the death of a loved one, and Aussie rules crowds go nuts around the country. These are the five quick hits from Australia's epic win over France.

title.children: Five quick hits — Matildas star mourns amid jubilation and the AFL is booed by fans as FIFA turned off

image.altText: A man in a green puffer jacket stands outside a Catholic church holding an old photo of a priest

items.synopsis: Brendan Watkins is one of thousands of children of Catholic priests who found their biological parents through DNA testing and social media. His birth wasn't the only secret his father kept.

title.children: Thousands of children of priests are finally finding their biological parents through DNA. But that's not the only secret being uncovered

image.altText: A sign prohibiting unmanned aerial vehicles flying over the area is on display near the Kremlin wall.

items.synopsis: Suspected Ukrainian drone strikes in Moscow are increasing with analysts saying mass attacks are likely. But questions remain around what Kyiv hopes to achieve and whether there will even be much impact.

title.children: Drone strikes on Moscow are ramping up with signs a 'truly massive' attack may not be far off

image.altText: Three post it notes in blue, white and yellow, with questions about sex and puberty written on them in messy handwriting.

items.synopsis: Young people's curiosity about sex is nothing new, but access to the internet and the terabytes of graphic pornography it hosts has given rise to a fresh set of concerns: if kids go looking for answers to their awkward questions on Google, what will they find?

title.children: The anonymous question a sex educator hears from kids nearly every day

image.altText: A road winds through blackened trees and flattened buildings.

items.synopsis: As the road to Lahaina was reopened on the fire-devastated Hawaiian island of Maui, residents hoped against hope that something would be left of their homes. They discovered a blackened hellscape.

title.children: 'Our town is gone': Heartbroken Hawaiians return to Lahaina to see a paradise lost

image.altText: Australia players run to celebrate after winning a Women's WOrld Cup quarterfinal against France.

items.synopsis: When someone asks you to tell the story of the night the Matildas made history, what will you say?

title.children: Matildas' World Cup win over France was the game that stopped a nation

image.altText: Mary Fowler, Sam Kerr, Caitlin Foord and Steph Catley of Australia celebrate the team’s victory

items.synopsis: The Matildas make history. And in the longest World Cup penalty shootout ever, France have been vanquished — and the internet went wild watching on.

title.children: 'I'm not built for this': How the internet reacted to the Matildas' penalty shootout triumph over France

image.altText: Ryan Gosling as Ken with bleached blonde hair and a denim shirt showcasing his abs

items.synopsis: If Barbie has taught us anything, it's that women can do anything. But an increasing number of people are saying young men and boys are now crying out for role models on how to be the best version of themselves.

title.children: It's not just Ken — why are boys and men feeling out in the cold?

image.altText: Both the doll and the box for Allan, Ken doll's friend.

items.synopsis: Collectors say the Barbie movie has sparked new fans of the dolls and there's one that "everyone wants in their collection".

title.children: The Barbie you may never have heard of is the hottest new doll in town

image.altText: OperaSunrise_10-08-2023 (2)

items.synopsis: This year the Sydney Opera House will celebrate its 50th anniversary. A living work of art, performance hub, tourist attraction and town square, it's always been about a lot more than the opera.

title.children: 'A miracle happening right here': How one of the world's most famous creations nearly wasn't built

image.altText: The corner of an empty room, grey carpet, white walls and windows with views of a city

items.synopsis: Whether it's the stealth wealth clothing that we're lusting after or the elevated sportswear that we're living with – our clothes are increasingly vanilla. And so are our homes.

title.children: 50 shades of greige: Why our clothes and homes became so monochromatic and blandly uniform

image.altText: Police car's lights

items.synopsis: A gyrocopter crash in dense bushland north of Newcastle has killed a 70-year-old man. A 53-year-old man has been flown to hospital in a serious condition.

title.children: A man dead and another seriously injured in gyrocopter crash

image.altText: Piles of rubbish including ropes, plastic bottles and PVC pipes are sprawled out on a table.

items.synopsis: Drink bottles from the 1980s, plastic straws and even 'nurdles' — they all wash up at Bathers Beach, south of Perth, with researchers trying to work out how effective bans on single-use plastics are.

title.children: On one of Perth's most littered beaches, researchers are concerned by rubbish that is decades old

image.altText: metal sign saying 'warmest welcome from Australia's hottest town'

items.synopsis: Known for its scorching summers, residents say Marble Bar has plenty of offer visitors all year round and a new airport is set to help them show it.

title.children: Can Australia's hottest town become its hottest tourist destination?

image.altText: A pile of peso banknotes with Star Wars characters painted on them.

items.synopsis: How did a country, once among the wealthiest in the world and uncomfortably similar to Australia, totally lose control of its economy?

title.children: Argentina and Australia once had eerily similar economies. How did one end up with 100 per cent inflation?

image.altText: A woman wearing a colourful dress and hijab wipes tears from her eyes.

items.synopsis: Khadidja is one of thousands of refugees who fled Sudan after a bloody civil war broke out between the army and a paramilitary group. Now she’s stuck inside one of the worst humanitarian crises on earth.

title.children: These Sudanese mums escaped a civil war. Now they fear their children will starve

image.altText: The face of a young man, who is holding a vape, is covered in vape smoke

items.synopsis: We need to know more about exactly what is inside vapes and e-cigarettes and how people use them so we can better understand and quantify the health risks in the real world, writes Alexander Larcombe.

title.children: Even experts don't know exactly what's in vapes. But the radioactive metal Russia uses to kill dissenters is on the list

image.altText: Dainty green tree frog with an inflated vocal sac under its chin

items.synopsis: Animals can make the strangest sounds. Tune into the noises made by some iconic species and find out how they make them.

title.children: Fish farts, snorting koalas, bonking frogs: How do animals make these crazy sounds?

image.altText: An Australian male tennis player pumps his right fist as he celebrates winning a point during a match.

items.synopsis: Australia's Alex de Minaur secures a comfortable straight-sets victory over Alejandro Davidovich Fokina to advance to the first ATP Masters 1000 final of his career.

title.children: Dominant de Minaur achieves career milestone after reaching Toronto final

image.altText: Harry Kane puts his hands through his hair as he reacts during his Bayern Munich debut.

items.synopsis: Ange Postecoglou is forced to prepare for his Premier League debut as Tottenham manager without Harry Kane, as the England captain moves to German giant Bayern Munich only a day before the Spurs' season-opening match.

image.altText: Two Carlton AFL players embrace as they celebrate during a win over Melbourne at the MCG.

image.altText: Grandma Erneti with Lara Lee cooking rendang in an Indonesian kitchen.

items.synopsis: Raised in Sydney by my Chinese-Indonesian father and Australian mother, the influence of my Timorese grandmother's cooking lingered long into adulthood, drawing me into the kitchen for a lesson in how to make rendang.

image.altText: A man in a black hat looks at the camera.

items.synopsis: Gedeon Shikiro nursed his massacred community members as they died in his arms at a United Nations refugee camp in Burundi. Nearly 20 years later, he is still fighting for justice.

title.children: Albury resident 'crying out' for justice 19 years after surviving horrific massacre in east Africa

image.altText: The outline of four women, kept anonymous, superimposed over shattered glass

items.synopsis: The Northern Territory coroner has already unravelled evidence of a system in dire need of reform, but her long-running inquiry into the NT's domestic violence response is far from over, resuming in Darwin on Monday.

title.children: Domestic violence inquiry examining killings of Aboriginal women to resume

image.altText: Noosa coastline fading into the Gold Coast skyline

items.synopsis: How will some of Queensland's most popular coastal regions look with 600,000 extra people, and how can they prepare?

title.children: Will the Gold, Sunshine coasts and Noosa be 'loved to death' as 600,000 people move in?

image.altText: An array of antiquities including Etruscan vases and ancient Roman coins and mosaics laid out at a press conference.

items.synopsis: Italian authorities celebrate the return of 266 antiquities worth tens of millions of dollars, including Etruscan vases and ancient Roman coins and mosaics, that were looted and sold to US museums and private collectors.

image.altText: A man pushes a woman floating on an inner tube through flood waters.

items.synopsis: Floods and landslides in Myanmar caused by monsoon rains leave at least five people dead — including several children — and force an estimated 48,000 people to flee their homes, according to the country's relief ministry.

image.altText: Image of a man smiling in front of green paddocks.

items.synopsis: In Australia's Top End, Munro Hardy, a modern cattleman, combines traditional ranching with cutting-edge technology. Managing data, targeted nutrition, and carbon mitigation are key focuses for the success of his small cattle station.

image.altText: a young aboriginal superhero standing on rock

items.synopsis: An art exhibition celebrating Indigenous superheroes is set to attract crowds in the Northern Territory. And it all started in 1973.

title.children: It's been 50 years since Indigenous artists created their own superhero. This is the legacy
